PiperOrigin-RevId: 366135105
Change-Id: Ie660dfbab51ff094c6ec8ca45646584b503b322d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/5211597d912dbef1242d7bf38b8bdf2b365e9872"},{"sha":"6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Move `SummaryWriter.{set_,}as_default()` impls up to the base class

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

Change-Id: Ifa6d88ba2e87f1eaae96fa3ea2fe3f6c5b73234a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3"},{"sha":"6a049381fb0989ea8f989dc9cea7e1fd588290a8","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"[retry]Use self.handle inside ResourceVariable to allow tf.distribute to customize
handle behavior

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

For legacy mode, we will maintain the existing behavior, since it hasn't
been reported as an issue, and we'd have to do additional work to
distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366135105
Change-Id: Ie660dfbab51ff094c6ec8ca45646584b503b322d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/5211597d912dbef1242d7bf38b8bdf2b365e9872"},{"sha":"6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Move `SummaryWriter.{set_,}as_default()` impls up to the base class

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

handle behavior

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

For legacy mode, we will maintain the existing behavior, since it hasn't
been reported as an issue, and we'd have to do additional work to
distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all

[{"sha":"158505edc3112f6dc68b3a17ffccb0a281a8e014","author":{"name":"Mihai Maruseac","email":"d291bc4e1ca4e2dccadea653e3e3371be2da8b06@google.com"},"message":"Switch TF filesystems to keep backwards compatibility.

Recent changes to enable modular TF can result in breakages or require majority of users to take quick steps to fix their broken code. Instead, we should enable the modular filsystems only if requested by an environment variable and use the legacy behavior in all cases.

In a future TF release, the cloud filesystems will come from different pip packages but we have to design the path towards that to ensure that no one in the TF ecosystem is broken by this. As we stand now, without this change most TF users will need to take action in a P0 basis and this is not desirable.

CC @yongtang, @kvignesh1420, @vnvo2409. Note that I also changed the name of the envvar to match the logic and you'll have to do the same for SIG IO code. Let's sync on SIG IO meeting to discuss further

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

For legacy mode, we will maintain the existing behavior, since it hasn't
been reported as an issue, and we'd have to do additional work to
distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

been reported as an issue, and we'd have to do additional work to
distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

handle behavior

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

For legacy mode, we will maintain the existing behavior, since it hasn't
been reported as an issue, and we'd have to do additional work to
distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

need to be observed by external systems.

Change-Id: Ie660dfbab51ff094c6ec8ca45646584b503b322d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/5211597d912dbef1242d7bf38b8bdf2b365e9872"},{"sha":"6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Move `SummaryWriter.{set_,}as_default()` impls up to the base class

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

Change-Id: Ifa6d88ba2e87f1eaae96fa3ea2fe3f6c5b73234a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3"},{"sha":"6a049381fb0989ea8f989dc9cea7e1fd588290a8","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"[retry]Use self.handle inside ResourceVariable to allow tf.distribute to customize
handle behavior

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

account.

For cross-compiling case, we can't generate the mutable schema easily.
It's complicated to run the target-specific flatc executable on the host
side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"
for using the immutable and mutable schema header.
If we use the immutable interface, use pack/unpack mechanism to update the
buffer content in the builder","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/31f79ad804cccc071b030a3950106558edd8b30e"},{"sha":"582bf0d3ac33fc10156f737c0d42f3adee54409a","author":{"name":"Jerry Shih","email":"56309c3330e60f9852e4b7519cac138302662305@gmail.com"},"message":"Update the tflite model "buffers" field checking rule.

If we don't use "--force-empty-vectors" flag[1] for flatc, the buffers
might be a null ptr if we serialize a model with zero buffers size(e.g.
all ops in model doesn't use const weights in model).
This commit relaxs the "buffers" null ptr checking for this situation,
and also updates the "subgraphs" checking for null ptr dereference.

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

Co-authored-by: Andrew Clark <git@andrewclark.io>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/b48b38af68c27fd401fe4b923a8fa0b229693cd4"},{"sha":"f8ef4ff571db3de73b0bfab566c1ce9d69c6582f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Flush discrete passive effects before paint (#21150)

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

For legacy mode, we will maintain the existing behavior, since it hasn't
been reported as an issue, and we'd have to do additional work to
distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all
passive effects from being treated this way.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/f8ef4ff571db3de73b0bfab566c1ce9d69c6582f"},{"sha":"0e96bdd4eefa0771fe1e7747bb79fd3c0e612b9c","author":{"name":"Lea Rosema","email":"3a9fc0a0496361fa6bf1cb635fc04f3d75877f43@gmail.com"},"message":"Remove my deadname from AUTHORS (#21152)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/0e96bdd4eefa0771fe1e7747bb79fd3c0e612b9c"},{"sha":"b9e4c10e99940ceaff77e1f6f4cb0c747e91acff","author":{"name":"Sebastian Markbåge","email":"8a279ae1320350359ecfec7a379763633f1edc4c@fb.com"},"message":"[Fizz] Implement all the DOM attributes and special cases (#21153)

For cross-compiling case, we can't generate the mutable schema easily.
It's complicated to run the target-specific flatc executable on the host
side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"
for using the immutable and mutable schema header.
If we use the immutable interface, use pack/unpack mechanism to update the

and also updates the "subgraphs" checking for null ptr dereference.

docker: Error response from daemon: OCI runtime create failed: container_linux.go:367: starting container process caused: process_linux.go:520: container init caused: rootfs_linux.go:60: mounting "/tmp/foo" to rootfs at "/home/suda/.local/share/docker/overlay2/b8e7ea02f6ef51247f7f10c7fb26edbfb308d2af8a2c77915260408ed3b0a8ec/merged/mnt" caused: operation not permitted: unknown.
```

Signed-off-by: Akihiro Suda <akihiro.suda.cz@hco.ntt.co.jp>

[{"sha":"31f79ad804cccc071b030a3950106558edd8b30e","author":{"name":"Jerry Shih","email":"56309c3330e60f9852e4b7519cac138302662305@gmail.com"},"message":"Update tflite versioning UpdateOpVersion() interface.

For cross-compiling case, we can't generate the mutable schema easily.

side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"

If we don't use "--force-empty-vectors" flag[1] for flatc, the buffers
might be a null ptr if we serialize a model with zero buffers size(e.g.
all ops in model doesn't use const weights in model).
This commit relaxs the "buffers" null ptr checking for this situation,
and also updates the "subgraphs" checking for null ptr dereference.

[{"sha":"31f79ad804cccc071b030a3950106558edd8b30e","author":{"name":"Jerry Shih","email":"56309c3330e60f9852e4b7519cac138302662305@gmail.com"},"message":"Update tflite versioning UpdateOpVersion() interface.

For cross-compiling case, we can't generate the mutable schema easily.
It's complicated to run the target-specific flatc executable on the host
side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"
for using the immutable and mutable schema header.
If we use the immutable interface, use pack/unpack mechanism to update the
buffer content in the builder","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/31f79ad804cccc071b030a3950106558edd8b30e"},{"sha":"582bf0d3ac33fc10156f737c0d42f3adee54409a","author":{"name":"Jerry Shih","email":"56309c3330e60f9852e4b7519cac138302662305@gmail.com"},"message":"Update the tflite model "buffers" field checking rule.

If we don't use "--force-empty-vectors" flag[1] for flatc, the buffers
might be a null ptr if we serialize a model with zero buffers size(e.g.
all ops in model doesn't use const weights in model).
This commit relaxs the "buffers" null ptr checking for this situation,
and also updates the "subgraphs" checking for null ptr dereference.

For cross-compiling case, we can't generate the mutable schema easily.
It's complicated to run the target-specific flatc executable on the host
side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"
for using the immutable and mutable schema header.
If we use the immutable interface, use pack/unpack mechanism to update the
buffer content in the builder","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/31f79ad804cccc071b030a3950106558edd8b30e"},{"sha":"582bf0d3ac33fc10156f737c0d42f3adee54409a","author":{"name":"Jerry Shih","email":"56309c3330e60f9852e4b7519cac138302662305@gmail.com"},"message":"Update the tflite model "buffers" field checking rule.

If we don't use "--force-empty-vectors" flag[1] for flatc, the buffers
might be a null ptr if we serialize a model with zero buffers size(e.g.
all ops in model doesn't use const weights in model).
This commit relaxs the "buffers" null ptr checking for this situation,
and also updates the "subgraphs" checking for null ptr dereference.

For cross-compiling case, we can't generate the mutable schema easily.
It's complicated to run the target-specific flatc executable on the host
side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"
for using the immutable and mutable schema header.
If we use the immutable interface, use pack/unpack mechanism to update the
buffer content in the builder","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/31f79ad804cccc071b030a3950106558edd8b30e"},{"sha":"582bf0d3ac33fc10156f737c0d42f3adee54409a","author":{"name":"Jerry Shih","email":"56309c3330e60f9852e4b7519cac138302662305@gmail.com"},"message":"Update the tflite model "buffers" field checking rule.

If we don't use "--force-empty-vectors" flag[1] for flatc, the buffers
might be a null ptr if we serialize a model with zero buffers size(e.g.
all ops in model doesn't use const weights in model).
This commit relaxs the "buffers" null ptr checking for this situation,
and also updates the "subgraphs" checking for null ptr dereference.

For cross-compiling case, we can't generate the mutable schema easily.
It's complicated to run the target-specific flatc executable on the host
side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"
for using the immutable and mutable schema header.
If we use the immutable interface, use pack/unpack mechanism to update the
buffer content in the builder","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/31f79ad804cccc071b030a3950106558edd8b30e"},{"sha":"582bf0d3ac33fc10156f737c0d42f3adee54409a","author":{"name":"Jerry Shih","email":"56309c3330e60f9852e4b7519cac138302662305@gmail.com"},"message":"Update the tflite model "buffers" field checking rule.

If we don't use "--force-empty-vectors" flag[1] for flatc, the buffers
might be a null ptr if we serialize a model with zero buffers size(e.g.
all ops in model doesn't use const weights in model).
This commit relaxs the "buffers" null ptr checking for this situation,
and also updates the "subgraphs" checking for null ptr dereference.

Since the build scripts will from now on be used in a CI/CD pipeline
they need to be strictly correct, not have bugs and not require manual
intervention. Therefore...

Fixes:
- The Windows build scripts did not incorporate Peter's fix, i.e. creating
  the 'config.h' file as a pre-cursor to the actual build.
  This is now fixed. (compare to build scripts for MacOS and Linux)
- The Windows build script did not include headers from '..\build'
  when compiling. They therefore did not work. This is now fixed.
  (this is a consequence of the JNI headers having been removed from
   source control in commit f395acec1238138ab293516b8819de27403b7219;
   the change was correctly implemented at the time in build scripts
   for Linux and MacOS but for some reason never in build scripts for
   Windows)
- The Windows build scripts will now stop on first error. (checks for
  exit code and abends immediately). The Linux and MacOS scripts do not
  need the same logic as such script can simply be executed with
  'bash -x <script>'.
- The content of the 'config.h' file is now echoed to the console
  as part of the build. This file is crucial to understand the fix
  for the bug reported in NETBEANS-1428.
- Since we will be creating 32-bit binaries on 64-bit platforms
  (because we can no longer find 32-bit hosts to build on):
  The Linux 32-bit script did not create a 32-bit binary for the
  'config' application, hence it produced an incorrect 'config.h' file.
- The Windows build scripts could not handle path names with spaces
  in them as is typical in Windows world. Hence the script did not
  work when executed from a GitHub Action workflow. This is now fixed.
  (too lazy to fix the same problem in the MacOS and Linux scripts;
   on those platforms the problem never manifests itself)
- MacOS script: was hardwired to use the installed JDK rather
  than using the JDK_HOME environment variable. This is now fixed.
- MacOS script: added comments and transparency about how the Universal
  Library mechanism works. (the result of the mechanism is that
  binaries for legacy platforms PowerPC and i386 architectures
  still exist in the bundle but do not receive bug fixes .. meaning
  they'll not as an example receive bug fix for NETBEANS-1428)
- The Windows build scripts used Unix line endings. Although Windows
  doesn't mind this when executing such script it has now been corrected.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/apache/netbeans/commits/504d66f049e21e7ac4d2205f5f5e2b6ed38bc77a"},{"sha":"1a862ab4f9cdb779bde27692b73694787700e45c","author":{"name":"Lars Bruun-Hansen","email":"f1aeec8b11565a668d6bc7a192ae3850d35af570@apache.org"},"message":"Added GitHub Actions workflow for building native library for lib.profiler

It's complicated to run the target-specific flatc executable on the host
side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"

need to be observed by external systems.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366135105
Change-Id: Ie660dfbab51ff094c6ec8ca45646584b503b322d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/5211597d912dbef1242d7bf38b8bdf2b365e9872"},{"sha":"6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Move `SummaryWriter.{set_,}as_default()` impls up to the base class

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

Change-Id: Ifa6d88ba2e87f1eaae96fa3ea2fe3f6c5b73234a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3"},{"sha":"6a049381fb0989ea8f989dc9cea7e1fd588290a8","author":{"name":"Ran Chen","email":"49043981742618ef538c755703712b0c26b8e5bf@google.com"},"message":"[retry]Use self.handle inside ResourceVariable to allow tf.distribute to customize

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

Change-Id: Ia2c15f9844e740146bd32001fdd858aee4f02d0a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/9d4b98b2a2f053678fdb42fa0aade5f9176355bc"},{"sha":"8d5bd34862d764ae0e2dbb0b2b66debc96e63903","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 366135105
Change-Id: Ie660dfbab51ff094c6ec8ca45646584b503b322d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/5211597d912dbef1242d7bf38b8bdf2b365e9872"},{"sha":"6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Move `SummaryWriter.{set_,}as_default()` impls up to the base class

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

handle behavior

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

Change-Id: Ia2c15f9844e740146bd32001fdd858aee4f02d0a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/9d4b98b2a2f053678fdb42fa0aade5f9176355bc"},{"sha":"8d5bd34862d764ae0e2dbb0b2b66debc96e63903","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

Change-Id: Ie660dfbab51ff094c6ec8ca45646584b503b322d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/5211597d912dbef1242d7bf38b8bdf2b365e9872"},{"sha":"6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Move `SummaryWriter.{set_,}as_default()` impls up to the base class

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

Change-Id: Ia2c15f9844e740146bd32001fdd858aee4f02d0a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/9d4b98b2a2f053678fdb42fa0aade5f9176355bc"},{"sha":"8d5bd34862d764ae0e2dbb0b2b66debc96e63903","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

Change-Id: Ia2c15f9844e740146bd32001fdd858aee4f02d0a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/9d4b98b2a2f053678fdb42fa0aade5f9176355bc"},{"sha":"8d5bd34862d764ae0e2dbb0b2b66debc96e63903","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

Change-Id: Ia2c15f9844e740146bd32001fdd858aee4f02d0a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/9d4b98b2a2f053678fdb42fa0aade5f9176355bc"},{"sha":"8d5bd34862d764ae0e2dbb0b2b66debc96e63903","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

* $ROCM_PATH/rocrand/include

while the popup switcher is open, the switcher can wind up in a state where it is listening
twice, and is hidden as soon as you release the mouse button.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

[{"sha":"c93c8deb85b2cf369ece3de787277754448d1f3f","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Updates to account for the removal of $ROCM_PATH/include/hiprand,rocrand dirs

The following dirs (which are soft-links really) will removed in a (near) future ROCm release. This commit updates `rocm_configure.bzl` to account for that change by explicitly copying over the header files (for `local_config_rocm` repo) from the following directories instead
* $ROCM_PATH/hiprand/include
* $ROCM_PATH/rocrand/include

Unfortunately making the above change also breaks the build, if the directories that will be going away, are still present. This is because we end up with two `make_copy_dir_rule`s in `rocm_configure.bzl` that try to write to the same destination dirs

```
ERROR: Traceback (most recent call last):
	File "/root/.cache/bazel/_bazel_root/efb88f6336d9c4a18216fb94287b8d97/external/local_config_rocm/rocm/BUILD", line 1588, column 8, in <toplevel>
		genrule(
Error in genrule: generated file 'rocm/include/hiprand/hiprand.h' in rule 'hiprand-include' conflicts with existing generated file from rule 'rocm-include', defined at /root/.cache/bazel/_bazel_root/efb88f6336d9c4a18216fb94287b8d97/external/local_config_rocm/rocm/BUILD:175:8
```

Change-Id: Ia2c15f9844e740146bd32001fdd858aee4f02d0a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/9d4b98b2a2f053678fdb42fa0aade5f9176355bc"},{"sha":"8d5bd34862d764ae0e2dbb0b2b66debc96e63903","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745"},{"sha":"47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remote provisioners require a connection config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e"},{"sha":"2b252ac677f1d99adcf08202c3047be2478a1055","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27910 from hashicorp/jbardin/remote-provisioners

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

For cross-compiling case, we can't generate the mutable schema easily.

side. So, we can't get the mutable interfaces used in UpdateOpVersion().

This commit checks a definition named "TFLITE_VERSION_USE_MUTABLE_SCHEMA"

This commit relaxs the "buffers" null ptr checking for this situation,
and also updates the "subgraphs" checking for null ptr dereference.

Change-Id: Ie660dfbab51ff094c6ec8ca45646584b503b322d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/5211597d912dbef1242d7bf38b8bdf2b365e9872"},{"sha":"6edaa9105a2cd91369ae69da0dd10993f77557b3","author":{"name":"Nick Felt","email":"e1c8e592cc7cfe6a58425c8d09efbf61173fd491@google.com"},"message":"Move `SummaryWriter.{set_,}as_default()` impls up to the base class

This anticipates some proliferation in the SummaryWriter class hierarchy by pulling the common logic around setting the writer as default up into the base class. This makes it slightly less of a pure interface, but the nature of these methods is such that they already are agnostic to the particular writer implementation (with the lone exception of `NoopSummaryWriter` which is a bit of a special case).

While I was at it, I've reworked `set_as_default()` to just call `as_default().__enter__()` to reduce duplication and the potential for divergence. This required defining the context manager as its own class versus just using `@contextmanager` for the reasons described in the code comment.

Lastly I fixed some docstrings to point to the base class instead of duplicating text.

handle behavior

I'm working on a new version of DistributedVariable which directly inherits from BaseResourceVariable. Its handle would return different resource tensors under different context, e.g. self.handle would be a replicated tensor under tpu context. This can avoid the need to use raw variable operations for special resource handles like tpu replicate handle or parallel device handle.

[{"sha":"bed49a52271925431209d2bd1bbed7dc831f2dc9","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

[{"sha":"53652a6194a18715ba9bad4099541d1261900870","author":{"name":"Aaron Greig","email":"5ba1c1d9a0898600b7121691670f4e8e38e7f830@codeplay.com"},"message":"Relax accuracy requirement on OpenCL MinEigenVal corner kernel test.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

Change-Id: Ia2c15f9844e740146bd32001fdd858aee4f02d0a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/9d4b98b2a2f053678fdb42fa0aade5f9176355bc"},{"sha":"8d5bd34862d764ae0e2dbb0b2b66debc96e63903","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.

[{"sha":"c93c8deb85b2cf369ece3de787277754448d1f3f","author":{"name":"Deven Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"Updates to account for the removal of $ROCM_PATH/include/hiprand,rocrand dirs

The following dirs (which are soft-links really) will removed in a (near) future ROCm release. This commit updates `rocm_configure.bzl` to account for that change by explicitly copying over the header files (for `local_config_rocm` repo) from the following directories instead
* $ROCM_PATH/hiprand/include
* $ROCM_PATH/rocrand/include

Unfortunately making the above change also breaks the build, if the directories that will be going away, are still present. This is because we end up with two `make_copy_dir_rule`s in `rocm_configure.bzl` that try to write to the same destination dirs

```
ERROR: Traceback (most recent call last):
	File "/root/.cache/bazel/_bazel_root/efb88f6336d9c4a18216fb94287b8d97/external/local_config_rocm/rocm/BUILD", line 1588, column 8, in <toplevel>
		genrule(
Error in genrule: generated file 'rocm/include/hiprand/hiprand.h' in rule 'hiprand-include' conflicts with existing generated file from rule 'rocm-include', defined at /root/.cache/bazel/_bazel_root/efb88f6336d9c4a18216fb94287b8d97/external/local_config_rocm/rocm/BUILD:175:8

Change-Id: Ia2c15f9844e740146bd32001fdd858aee4f02d0a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/9d4b98b2a2f053678fdb42fa0aade5f9176355bc"},{"sha":"8d5bd34862d764ae0e2dbb0b2b66debc96e63903","author":{"name":"Fergus Henderson","email":"f0ea4d8809145d4adcbe42010b047377f121dc12@google.com"},"message":"Add protected method MutableOpResolver::ChainOpResolver.

[Rolling forward Change I6ba6f54afefe4e675dd5ac8c9749adfb94735cfd
after a couple of spurious auto-rollbacks.]

This is similar to 'AddAll', except that
(1) it's argument is an OpResolver, whereas 'AddAll' requires
    another MutableOpResolver, and
(2) it does not make a copy of the OpResolver's ops, and does not take
    ownership, so the argument OpResolver needs to live as long as the
    MutableOpResolver.

Under the hood, this works by keeping a vector of OpResolver pointers
to fall back to, and changing the FindOp methods to try these if
the op can't be found.
